data.content:
Yes! MSTest v3.3+ supports **strongly-typed tuples** with `[DynamicData]`, eliminating the `object[]` indirection:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` — tuple elements are type-checked at compile time
- Square brackets `[…]` → parentheses `(…)` for each test case (tuples instead of arrays)

The test method signature stays the same — MSTest destructures the tuple into the method parameters automatically. If you add or remove a field from the tuple but forget to update the test method (or vice versa), you'll get a compile error instead of a runtime failure.
